">           Similarly, before we look at the instances of genocide or attempted genocide in <i>Blood Music</i> and <i>The Terminator</i>, we need to delineate what exactly is considered "genocide." According to the <i>Convention on the Prevention and Punishment of the Crime of Genocide</i>, which was adopted by the United Nations General Assembly in 1948, genocide includes any of the following actions. The actions below must destroy either in whole or in part destroy a group.

                               1. Kills members of this group.
                               2. Causes serious harm to members of the group(physically or mentally)
                               3. Deliberately inflicts on the group's conditions of life in order to bring physical destruction, in whole or in part.
                               4. Imposes measures to prevent births within the group.
                               5. Forcibly transfers children of the group to another group.

           As a result, we can clearly see that humans do attempt to commit genocide upon the noocytes in <i>Blood Music</i>; the USSR tries to "launch a full-scale nuclear-strike on North America,"(198) in order to kill many or all of the noocytes that have overrun and taken over the land. This correlates with the action of killing members of the noocyte group. Additionally, deciding to nuclear strike would inflict great devastation on the environment that the noocytes inhabit. This would affect the noocytes' conditions of life, and may bring upon either partial or entire physical descrution. In <i>The Terminator</i>, we also see humanity engaging in genocide against the androids. John Connor is leading the human Resistance, which fights the androids, with the intent to kill them or to cause serious physical harm to them. Also, we may also see part five of the definition of genocide in play. The human Resistance is forcibly reprogramming Terminators in order to transfer them to humanity's side. For example, the android played by Arnold Schwarzenegger is reprogrammed to save John. As a result, it now risks its own embodiment in order to protect John's life from the android trying to assassinate him. Thus, we see humanity engaging in genocide in both <i>Blood Music</i> and <i>The Terminator</i>.</p>
